Life in Majuro also gave me the opportunity to spend time relaxing in the sun to embrace the balmy island life, but in so doing, spend all day every day after in a very short time in heavy duty skin protection with powerful sunblock.

The beach on one of my morning runs, taken at 7am in the morning

After the sun protecting meant using a very heavy mousturizer and sunblock to protect at all times before I put on makeup, but along with all of these clothing, lotions and everything else that protected me from the sun, I also needed to be on guard much more vigilant then I was, knowing these issues better. I knew that the sun can be a great killer and of my skin cancer issues, I also knew that the potential was there too. The trips to Rhode Island year after year when I would not expose myself to the level I did in Majuro were part of that, as well as the use of the evolved modern medical advances that I have come since I was assigned to Elmendorf AFB near McChord AFB in Washington State when my granddaughter was 7 years old, was when I found out the melanoma danger.
